WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.960
 structures. Structures is one of the most beautiful parts of C like pointers. It's a user defined type that contains sort of one or more types within it.

00:00:12.960 --> 00:00:22.960
 We call things like x and y, in this case, members of the structure. X is a member of the struct point and y is a member of the struct point.

00:00:22.960 --> 00:00:31.960
 The dot operator allows us to take a variable that is a structure variable that has all these members within it and then access the members of the structure.

00:00:31.960 --> 00:00:42.960
 So an example, kr0601.c, we have struct point open curly brace, double x semicolon, double y semicolon, closed curly brace semicolon.

00:00:42.960 --> 00:00:59.960
 And this defines a new type. It doesn't allocate any data. And then we say struct point p1, p2 semicolon. And that actually allocates two points, which is four doubles named p1 and each point is p1 and p2.

00:00:59.960 --> 00:01:12.960
 Then I say p1.x equals 3.0 and I say p1.y equals 4.0 and then I say p2 equals p1, which copies all the fields into the corresponding locations in p2.

00:01:12.960 --> 00:01:24.960
 And then I print them out and I get three and four. And so that's basic structures. Simple, clean, elegant, understand every line of this, memorize it.

00:01:24.960 --> 00:01:31.960
 When you do a, in a sense, call by value with a structure, the entire structure is placed on the stack.

00:01:31.960 --> 00:01:39.960
 And so you don't want to make structures too gigantically big. You know, if they're like 10 to 40 bytes of characters, they're not all that bad.

00:01:39.960 --> 00:01:54.960
 But when we make struct point pm and set x and y to three and four, and then we call funk with funk open print, pm closed print, pm is a structure that is in the scope of the main program.

00:01:54.960 --> 00:01:59.960
 And then we're calling funk and passing it in. And then we're accepting it as a structure inside of funk.

00:01:59.960 --> 00:02:09.960
 And the key thing there is at this point, it's a sort of copy of a call by value where the entire structure is allocated on the stack and then passed into funk.

00:02:09.960 --> 00:02:18.960
 So if we change it inside funk, pf.x equals 9.0 and pf.y equals 8.0, it changes locally and we can print it out.

00:02:18.960 --> 00:02:30.960
 And then when it returns, the pm that's in the main program is unchanged. And that's because the entire structure, pm, is duplicated into the stack frame for function funk.

00:02:30.960 --> 00:02:34.960
 Operating inside function funk, we're only messing with the copy that's in our stack frame.

00:02:34.960 --> 00:02:39.960
 And then when we sort of undo that, it restores pm back to the way it was.

00:02:39.960 --> 00:02:45.960
 So those are just plain structures, but pointers to structures are where we get a lot more powerful.

00:02:45.960 --> 00:02:49.960
 So here we have another same struct with a double x and a double y.

00:02:49.960 --> 00:03:00.960
 And now we say struct point pt, which is a regular old variable, and then star pp, which is a pointer to a structure, an address of a structure.

00:03:00.960 --> 00:03:07.960
 And you can take the address of a structure just like you take the address of an integer, a structure is a very fundamental type.

00:03:07.960 --> 00:03:15.960
 So pp equals ampersand pt copies the address of the actual structure pt into the variable pp.

00:03:15.960 --> 00:03:23.960
 pt.x equals 3.0 or open pp star pp close pp.y equals 4.0.

00:03:23.960 --> 00:03:29.960
 So if we have a pointer to a structure, we have to use the asterisk to sort of look up the actual structure.

00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:33.960
 And then we can do structure things with it, like set the .y value.

00:03:33.960 --> 00:03:38.960
 There's a shortcut, take an address, dereference it with the asterisk and then use the dot.

00:03:38.960 --> 00:03:46.960
 They're combined into kind of what we call the arrow operator, which is pp dash greater than y,

00:03:46.960 --> 00:03:50.960
 which is the same as open pp star pp close pp.x.

00:03:50.960 --> 00:03:57.960
 And so this we call it the arrow operator. And so it's kind of a shorthand and it's used all the time.

00:03:57.960 --> 00:04:01.960
 And you'll see when we look later at things like PHP, they adopted this arrow operator.

00:04:01.960 --> 00:04:09.960
 Most other object oriented languages tend to use the dot operator, but others use the arrow operator.

00:04:09.960 --> 00:04:19.960
 So if we're going to pass a structure by reference, you use the ampersand in the call and the asterisk inside the function.

00:04:19.960 --> 00:04:26.960
 So we create struct point pm, set x and y within that to 3 and 4 respectively.

00:04:26.960 --> 00:04:34.960
 Then we print it out and then we call func, but now we call it with ampersand pm, which says pass in the address of pm.

00:04:34.960 --> 00:04:40.960
 And then in the function, we take in pp and we declare its type as struct point star pp,

00:04:40.960 --> 00:04:45.960
 which means we are getting as a parameter an address, not the value.

00:04:45.960 --> 00:04:51.960
 And then we use the arrow operator, pp arrow x equals 9, pp arrow y equals 8.

00:04:51.960 --> 00:04:59.960
 We print that in the function, but because pp just points to pm, it's also changed in the copy that's in the main.

00:04:59.960 --> 00:05:03.960
 So pm is being changed at the moment that pp is being changed.

00:05:03.960 --> 00:05:10.960
 And so when it comes back, you see that the value is 9 and 8 outside of the function.

00:05:10.960 --> 00:05:15.960
 So this is simply passing by reference. It almost we better call it pass by address.

00:05:15.960 --> 00:05:23.960
 So if you take a look at the stack frame, what you see is when we're calling func open paren ampersand pm close paren,

00:05:23.960 --> 00:05:31.960
 we are making a copy of the address and putting that into the stack frame and then passing that stack frame into func.

00:05:31.960 --> 00:05:40.960
 And so now func has an address of something. It happens to not be in its domain, meaning that pm is still in main.

00:05:40.960 --> 00:05:46.960
 But we can work with the arrow operator and actually make changes in the underlying object.

00:05:46.960 --> 00:05:54.960
 And so the key there is that you could change pp, but pp arrow x, you're actually changing the single copy that is in pm at that point.

00:05:54.960 --> 00:05:59.960
 Storage allocation. Now, pretty soon we're going to be dynamically allocating things.

00:05:59.960 --> 00:06:06.960
 We've always said that, oh, you create a char array of char with open bracket 10. There's 10 things in that.

00:06:06.960 --> 00:06:13.960
 What if we want more? And we've said you can't reallocate this stuff. But now we have this thing we're going to start allocating.

00:06:13.960 --> 00:06:17.960
 So it turns out when you're allocating things, you have to know how big they are.

00:06:17.960 --> 00:06:24.960
 OK, and so there's this size of operator. So size of so we take struct point pt and star pp,

00:06:24.960 --> 00:06:30.960
 which means we have a structure with two doubles in it and then a pointer to a structure with two doubles of it.

00:06:30.960 --> 00:06:36.960
 And we simply say, what is the size of the structure? And it's 16 because each double is eight.

00:06:36.960 --> 00:06:43.960
 And then what is the size of a pointer to a structure? And that is eight because eight is how big addresses are.

00:06:43.960 --> 00:06:48.960
 The fact that doubles and addresses happen to both be the same thing is not relevant here.

00:06:48.960 --> 00:06:53.960
 Addresses are on most C systems, eight characters.

00:06:53.960 --> 00:06:58.960
 You can also, because it's an operator, not just give it a variable, but also give it a type.

00:06:58.960 --> 00:07:02.960
 So we can say size of open paren struct point close paren.

00:07:02.960 --> 00:07:09.960
 And that also will be 16 because the size of a struct, if we were going to allocate it, is 16 characters.

00:07:09.960 --> 00:07:14.960
 So size of returns the size of something in characters.

00:07:14.960 --> 00:07:21.960
 And so we have this function called malloc. And malloc, you have to include stdlib.h to do it.

00:07:21.960 --> 00:07:26.960
 And so now what we're going to do is create the structure point again and we're going to create a pointer.

00:07:26.960 --> 00:07:35.960
 And we're going to not actually allocate it. So that struct point star pp allocates an eight character address, not the actual double to doubles.

00:07:35.960 --> 00:07:43.960
 Now what we do is we say pp equals first, and we're casting this, we're casting the returned address from malloc.

00:07:43.960 --> 00:07:52.960
 Paren struct point star paren, close paren, that is casting it to a pointer to a struct, a pointer to a point.

00:07:52.960 --> 00:07:58.960
 And then we say malloc open paren size of struct point close paren, close paren.

00:07:58.960 --> 00:08:02.960
 And so that says malloc 16 because a struct point is 16 characters.

00:08:02.960 --> 00:08:08.960
 So malloc goes and finds some free memory for us and its pool of free memory and gives us back an address,

00:08:08.960 --> 00:08:14.960
 which we then convert to a pointer to a point. And then we store that in pp.

00:08:14.960 --> 00:08:22.960
 And at that point we have data, we have a working structure and we can set the x and the y value just as the normal way,

00:08:22.960 --> 00:08:29.960
 whether we use the arrow operator or the star and dot operators, we can access that information.

