 So I want to show you how you delete an item from a singly linked list.

00:14:56.960 --> 00:15:05.960
 So first you've got to find it. You've got to do the walking of the linked list which I just showed you. You've got to walk through and you've got to find the item that you want to delete.

00:15:05.960 --> 00:15:13.960
 Now if you walk through and you don't find it there's nothing to delete. So our goal is to delete the line "is".

00:15:13.960 --> 00:15:20.960
 But you've got to handle three cases. There's the easy one which is where the thing you found is in the middle of the list.

00:15:20.960 --> 00:15:26.960
 Or if the thing that you found is at the start of the list or if the thing you found is the last item in the list.

00:15:26.960 --> 00:15:36.960
 And again you've got to draw pictures and you may have to draw them separately because we're going to be adjusting head and tail in addition to the next values.

00:15:36.960 --> 00:15:45.960
 Now it turns out when you're going to do a delete you want to not only track the current item in the list you want to track the previous item in the list.

00:15:45.960 --> 00:15:54.960
 So as you're walking down the list you look your current moves ahead and prev moves right behind it. So prev trails current by one item.

00:15:54.960 --> 00:16:02.960
 You can see that current the "is" line is the one we're going to delete and it's pretty simple.

00:16:02.960 --> 00:16:08.960
 The only real thing that you've got to change is you take prev next and you point it at curr next.

00:16:08.960 --> 00:16:18.960
 So you can see on the right hand side that the little link from the "c" to the "fun" has just bypassed the "is".

00:16:18.960 --> 00:16:24.960
 Now you do have to deallocate the struct "l" node and the string but that's pretty much all you need to do.

00:16:24.960 --> 00:16:33.960
 And so the middle is really easy. You find it, you keep track of prev, you have current and then you just kind of bypass it by moving next.

00:16:33.960 --> 00:16:38.960
 So that's the easy one. The next thing that you got to do is what if it's the first node?

